listing.description:
Speak & Translate is an indispensable voice and text translator that allows you to communicate effectively in any corner of the globe.

EXCELLENT TRANSLATION OPTIONS:
* Brand new Apple Watch App
* New Snap Mode: Just snap a picture of any text or object you want translated!
* Apple Speech Recognition Technology support - real-time voice recognition significantly enhances the speed of your translations
* 117 languages for text translations
* 54 languages for voice translations
* Language detection for text-to-text mode: if you don't know what the language of the source text is, select Detect language from the language list
* iCloud integration: the history of your translations is synchronized across all your Apple devices
* Voice settings: choose male or female voice and its speed

Note: The Free version may be subject to limitations (ex. number of daily translations) and the limitations are subject to change.

Parts of service translated by Microsoft®. Parts of service translated by Google Translate™.  

Speech to speech translations are supported between: 
Arabic, Basque, Catalan, Chinese (Cantonese, Mandarin, Taiwan), Czech, Danish, Dutch (The Netherlands), English (Australian, Canadian, Indian, UK, US), Finnish, French, French (Canada), Galician, German, Greek, Hebrew, Hindi, Hungarian, Indonesian, Italian, Japanese, Korean, Moldavian, Norwegian, Polish, Portuguese, Portuguese (Brazil), Romanian, Russian, Slovak, Spanish, Spanish (Mexican), Swedish, Thai, Turkish. 

Speech to text translations are supported between:
Afrikaans, Bulgarian, Croatian, Filipino, Icelandic, Latin, Lithuanian, Malay, Persian, Serbian, Slovenian, Ukrainian, Vietnamese, Zulu.

Text to text translations are supported between 117 languages, to check out the list of languages please visit Developer Website Link (http://www.apalon.com/speak_and_translate.html).

Get Speak & Translate Premium and enjoy:
- Unlimited translations
- Offline mode for text translations
- Ads-free translation experience

* Choose from different subscription options. Our standard subscription options are:

Speak and Translate Premium
1-month Subscription- $5.99
1-year Subscription- $69.99

* Subscription payments will be charged to your iTunes account at confirmation of your purchase and upon commencement of each renewal term. Subscription with a free trial period will automatically renew to a paid subscription. You can cancel your subscription or free trial in the iTunes settings at least 24-hours before the end of the free trial period. The cancellation will take effect the day after the last day of the current subscription period and you will be downgraded to the free service. 
* Please note: any unused portion of a free trial period (if offered) will be forfeited when you purchase a premium subscription during the free trial period.

For complete access to all Speak & Translate features, you will need to allow access to the following:

*Location – so that automatic language selection can be enabled for your host country when traveling.
*Microphone & Speech Recognition – so that speech-to-speech translations will work.
*Notifications – so that you can keep informed about new app features and interesting language facts.

EULA: http://www.apalon.com/terms_of_use.html

Privacy Policy: http://apalon.com/privacy_policy.html

AdChoices: http://www.apalon.com/privacy_policy.html#4

check.description: This test statically checks the app configuration and flags is App Transport Security (ATS) is disabled universally.
As the app is running on the device, any calls to CommonCrypto are monitored. if any of those calls encrypt sensitive data using a known insecure cryptography method, that is flagged in this finding.

While the app is running on a physical device, this test dynamically detects whether the app delegate explicitly revoked permissions for allowing usage of 3rd party keyboards by returning `NO` for the identifier `UIApplicationKeyboardExtensionPointIdentifier`.

While the application runs, cryptographic APIs are monitored to identify any insecure usage of cryptographic algorithms or primitives.
In this case, insecure cryptographic hashing algorithms are monitored.

As the app is running on a physical device, the testing platform looks for text entry fields.
This test flags UI text objects observed with the autocorrectionType set to `UITextAutocorrectionTypeYes` or `UITextAutocorrectionTypeDefault`.

It is easy to expose all object properties without considering their individual sensitivity, relying on clients to perform the data filtering before displaying it to the user.
The issues displayed in the table below may also constitute an API excessive data exposure concern.
Careful consideration to the API endpoints below and the issues observed should be given based on the organization's security and privacy standards.

While the app is running on a physical device, CommonCrypto API requests are examined to detect usage of insecure encryption algorithms, encryption modes, hashing algorithms or insufficient key derivation rounds.
After exercising the app, local application files and storage locations were inspected for sensitive data. For this check, instances of the Vendor ID were searched for.
After exercising the app, local application files and storage locations were inspected for sensitive data. For this check, instances of the ZIP Code were searched for.
API endpoint interactions observed through the course of dynamic/behavior testing.
Detects use of platform-provided secure deterministic random bit generation (DRBG) services.
CommonCrypto calls are analyzed to determine if any sensitive data is protected using symmetric encryption, hash-based message authentication codes, and digests.
Detects use of platform-provided preferences storage on iOS.
This section highlights any activity where the app calls the iOS Keychain. The table in this section displays when keychain items are created, deleted, or queried in some way.
This test looks for the existence of a privacy policy during app runtime.

Software Development Kits (SDKs) and  Frameworks are self-contained, reusable chunks of code and resources that you can import into any number of apps that can be shared across iOS, tvOS, watchOS, and macOS apps.
These are similar to frameworks used in other languages (e.g. `node_modules`).
The table below shows frameworks that were detected during dynamic analysis.
As the application is running, we monitor any interaction with SQLite databases in order to understand how the application interacts with its data.

Debug logs are generally designed to be used to detect and correct flaws in an application.
These logs can leak sensitive information that may help an attacker create a more powerful attack.
The table below shows any OSLog messages detected while performing dynamic analysis.
This unified logging system stores messages in memory and in a data store, rather than writing to text-based log files.
URLs observed to be opened by the application via calls to -[UIApplication openURL:] while running the app on a physical device.

In this section, any certificates in use by the application are displayed in a table, and includes the type of key, number of bits, serial number, URL, and common name associated with each certificate.
As the application is running, we monitor the network communications in order to understand where the application is sending its data.

An NSURLConnection object allows the developer to load the contents of a URL by providing a URL request object. By performing dynamic analysis of the iOS application, we are able to provide details on network connections made by the app. The table below highlights each of these connections, and provides contextual data including the type of NSURLConnection, as well as the associated method, URL, body, status code, and data.
CFURLConnection requests are analyzed to determine if any sensitive data is transmitted over the network.

The testing platform attempts to bypass the security controls of TLS communications and provide a window into the data that is being sent within those communications. This test does not provide data on the validity of certificate validation or pinning within an application.

As an example, this finding can be used to identify where sensitive information such as usernames, passwords, GPS coordinates and phone numbers are being sent and auditing that the information is not being sent somewhere that it should not be going.
Checks for embedded URLs in the source code, which can point to sensitive company servers or assets and provide valuable information to potential attackers.

The following table highlights a list of the potential behaviors that may be observed while interacting with the application, a brief description of each behavior and what it might be used for, and the applicable architecture (MACH-O slice) in which that behavior was detectable.

Entitlements confer specific capabilities or security permissions to an iOS application.
The table below shows the entitlement along with the value, as detected using static analysis.

This is an informational section which provides details about the compiled binary that were observed during our dynamic analysis of the application.
Examples of the metadata shown in this section include the different architecture versions the app is compiled to run on, various flags set in the application, bundle information, identified behaviors and important libraries, and more.
Many of these items are already being analyzed and separated out into their own individual checks, resulting in a "Pass" result or a "Low/Medium/High" risk issue.

Authentication is often implemented incorrectly, allowing attackers to compromise authentication tokens or to exploit implementation flaws to assume other user's identities temporarily or permanently. The following issues should be carefully reviewed for how they may impact the application or organization's API(s).

Determines whether the application is properly validating the Certificate Authority (CA). To verify that Certificate Validation is being properly performed, an attempt is made to intercept network traffic from the app using a certificate that was not signed by a CA (a self-signed certificate). If the certificate is accepted by the app, all data that uses that connection is decrypted.

Determines whether the application is properly verifying that the certificate's hostname matches the intended hostname for the network communication. To verify that Hostname Verification is being properly performed, an attempt is made to intercept traffic from the app using a certificate that was signed by a valid Certificate Authority (CA) and issued for a domain that will not match the endpoint in which the app is establishing a connection with. If the app accepts a CA-signed certificate issued to a mismatched hostname, it may be attributed to issues in the Hostname Verification process. If the certificate is accepted, the traffic is decrypted.
